    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-10-09T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-10-09T12:00:00-05:00" n="1414"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1414">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 867.4016/162</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Turkey</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_MH1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Morgenthau</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the</hi>
                    <gloss type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Secretary of State</hi>
                    </gloss>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Constantinople</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-10-09T19:00:00+02:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 9, 1915, 7 p. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received October 12, 8.15 a. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1130. Your 1165, October 6. Have not received your 973, 974, 972, 1010,
                        1028.<note n="1" xml:id="d1414fn1">Not printed.</note> Impossible to say
                    definitely that permission for Armenians generally can be secured. When contents
                    your 1023<note n="1" xml:id="d1414fn2">Not printed.</note> were [communicated]
                    to the Sublime Porte, it stated that as most of the deported Armenians are still
                        <hi rend="italic">en route</hi> it is advisable to wait for a short time
                    until deportation has ceased and caravans have reached their destination. The
                    Sublime Porte will know then their whereabouts and will consider applications
                    for emigration to United States. Until now, very few Armenians have been
                    permitted to leave Turkey. All had to go through Constantinople. On receipt of
                    names and particulars I shall do my best to secure permission at the opportune
                    moment.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MH1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Morgenthau</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
